      "content": "The reflection vector can be calculated using the formula `R = I - 2 * (I · N) * N`, where `I` is the incident vector and `N` is the normalized surface normal. Since your test vectors appear to be already normalized, you can directly apply this without an explicit normalization step in this specific case.\n\nHere is the implementation for your ray trayer prototype:\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef reflect(incident, normal):\n    return incident - 2 * np.dot(incident, normal) * normal\n\n# Test 1: Simple integer case\ninc1 = np.array([1, -1, 0])\nnorm1 = np.array([0, 1, 0])\nassert np.array_equal(reflect(inc1, norm1), np.array([1, 1, 0])), f\"Test 1 Failed\"\n\n# Test 2: Diagonal case\ninc2 = np.array([1, -1, 1])\nnorm2 = np.array([0, 1, 0])\nassert np.array_equal(reflect(inc2, norm2), np.array([1, 1, 1])), f\"",
